n-formed by Public Interest -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLatin American cities have always been characterized by a strong tension between what is vaguely described as their formal and informal dimensions. However, the terms formal and informal refer not only to the physical aspect of cities but also to their entire socio-political fabric. Informal cities and settlements exceed the structures of order, control and homogeneity that one expects to find in a formal city; therefore the contributors to this volume - from such disciplines as architecture, urban planning, anthropology, urban design, cultural and urban studies and sociology - focus on alternative methods of analysis in order to study the phenomenon of urban informality. This book provides a thorough review of the work that is currently being carried out by scholars, practitioners and governmental institutions, in and outside Latin America, on the question of informal cities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aArchitecture and societyzLatin America. 0aCities and townszLatin America. 0aSociology, UrbanzLatin America. 7aARCHITECTURE / General.2bisacsh1 aAllen, Lea Knudsen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBrandão, Zeca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrillembourg, Alfredo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFiori, Jorge, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreene, Margarita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHernández, Felipe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHernández, Felipe, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJirón,